    <select1 appearance="button" ref="/chapter2_2_exam_en/c2_2_q1">
      <label>1. Which newborns should receive KMC?</label>
      <item>
        <label>Newborns who weigh less than 2000g and are born preterm</label>
        <value>1</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>Newborns who weigh over 2500g</label>
        <value>2</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>None of the above</label>
        <value>3</value>
      </item>
    </select1>
    <select1 appearance="button" ref="/chapter2_2_exam_en/c2_2_q2">
      <label>2. How long should KMC be continued each day?</label>
      <item>
        <label>A total of at least 20 hours, including the day and night time</label>
        <value>1</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>A total of at least 12 hours, including day and night time</label>
        <value>2</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>A total of at least 2 hours, including day and night time</label>
        <value>3</value>
      </item>
    </select1>
    <select1 appearance="button" ref="/chapter2_2_exam_en/c2_2_q3">
      <label>3. For how long should KMC be continued?</label>
      <item>
        <label>Until the newborn reaches 2500g weight</label>
        <value>1</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>Until the newborn completes 40 weeks of Gestational Age</label>
        <value>2</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>All of the above</label>
        <value>3</value>
      </item>
    </select1>
    <select appearance="button" ref="/chapter2_2_exam_en/c2_2_q4">
      <label>4. What are the correct steps of expressing breast milk?</label>
      <item>
        <label>1.    Prior to expressing milk, mothers should wash their hands with soap and water and clean their breasts with water, but not soap.</label>
        <value>1</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>2.    Place a clean container below the breast to collect milk.</label>
        <value>2</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>3.    Massage the breast gently towards the nipple.</label>
        <value>3</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>4.    Place your thumb and index finger opposite each other just outside the areola.</label>
        <value>4</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>5.    Now press back towards the chest, then gently squeeze to express milk.</label>
        <value>5</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>6.    Repeat step 4 at different segments around the areola.</label>
        <value>6</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>7.    Express breast until milk drips, then express the other breast.</label>
        <value>7</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>8.    Alternate between breasts 5-6 times (20-30minutes).</label>
        <value>8</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>9.    Massage breasts and apply warm compressions prior to or during expression to improve milk flow.</label>
        <value>9</value>
      </item>
    </select>
    <select appearance="button" ref="/chapter2_2_exam_en/c2_2_q5">
      <label>5. What are the steps of feeding the baby by cup or spoon?</label>
      <item>
        <label>1. For cup feeding, take a measured amount of milk in a clean cup.</label>
        <value>1</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>2. Baby should be awake and held semi-upright in caregiver’s lap.</label>
        <value>2</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>3. Place a small piece of cloth on baby’s chest to catch the spillage and touch the edge of the cup to the outer side of lower lip.</label>
        <value>3</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>4. Begin by dripping a small amount of milk into the baby’s mouth.</label>
        <value>4</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>5. Let the baby swallow before dripping more milk.</label>
        <value>5</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>6. When using a cup, allow the baby to lick the milk directly rather than pouring milk into the mouth.</label>
        <value>6</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>7. Tip/tilt the cup slightly so that the milk reaches the baby’s lip.</label>
        <value>7</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>8. Try avoiding pouring milk into baby’s mouth.</label>
        <value>8</value>
      </item>
    </select>
    <select1 appearance="button" ref="/chapter2_2_exam_en/c2_2_q6">
      <label>6. What are the Danger Signs of a Newborn?</label>
      <item>
        <label>Temperature below 35.5°C and over 37.5°C</label>
        <value>1</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>Severe chest in-drawing, breathing more than 60 times per minute</label>
        <value>2</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>Not feeding well, movement only when stimulated</label>
        <value>3</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>All of the above</label>
        <value>4</value>
      </item>
    </select1>
    <select1 appearance="button" ref="/chapter2_2_exam_en/c2_2_q7">
      <label>7. Severe chest in-drawing is defined by:</label>
      <item>
        <label>Blue coloration of the skin</label>
        <value>1</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>Indentation of sub-coastal areas with each breath</label>
        <value>2</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>Temperature is 35.5°C</label>
        <value>3</value>
      </item>
    </select1>
    <select1 appearance="button" ref="/chapter2_2_exam_en/c2_2_q8">
      <label>8. How is convulsion recognized?</label>
      <item>
        <label ref="jr:itext('/chapter2_2_exam_en/c2_2_q8/1:label')"/>
        <value>1</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label ref="jr:itext('/chapter2_2_exam_en/c2_2_q8/2:label')"/>
        <value>2</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label ref="jr:itext('/chapter2_2_exam_en/c2_2_q8/3:label')"/>
        <value>3</value>
      </item>
    </select1>
    <select1 appearance="button" ref="/chapter2_2_exam_en/c2_2_q9">
      <label>9. Which antibiotic is suitable for 0-7 days’ newborn as treatment for Danger Signs?</label>
      <item>
        <label>Injection Ampicillin 60mg/kg dose, 12 hourly for 7 days and Injection Gentamycin 5mg/kg dose 24 hourly for 7 days</label>
        <value>1</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>Injection Ampicillin 50mg/kg dose 12 hourly for 6 days and Injection Gentamycin 5mg/kg dose 24 hourly for 7 days</label>
        <value>2</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>Injection Ampicillin 50 mg/kg dose, 12 hourly for 7 days and Injection Gentamycin 5mg/kg dose 24 hourly for 7 days</label>
        <value>3</value>
      </item>
    </select1>
    <select appearance="button" ref="/chapter2_2_exam_en/c2_2_q10">
      <label>10. What are the characteristics of pathological Jaundice?</label>
      <item>
        <label>Appears on the 1st day of life</label>
        <value>1</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>Bilirubin level rises rapidly (70.5 mg/dl/hour)</label>
        <value>2</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>Jaundice extending up to palm and sole of feet</label>
        <value>3</value>
      </item>
    </select>
    <select1 appearance="button" ref="/chapter2_2_exam_en/c2_2_q11">
      <label>11. What are the common investigations done for diagnosis of Jaundice?</label>
      <item>
        <label>Serum Hb, PCV, serum bilirubin, CBC, Blood grouping</label>
        <value>1</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>Serum Hb, PCV, serum bilirubin, CBC, Blood grouping, C6PD, Thyroid function</label>
        <value>2</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>Serum Hb, PCV, serum bilirubin</label>
        <value>3</value>
      </item>
    </select1>
    <select1 appearance="button" ref="/chapter2_2_exam_en/c2_2_q12">
      <label>12. What is the indication of phototherapy?</label>
      <item>
        <label>If Jaundice is on day 1</label>
        <value>1</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>If Jaundice is on day 1 and involving palm and feet</label>
        <value>2</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>If Jaundice is on day 1 and involving palm and feet, baby is premature</label>
        <value>3</value>
      </item>
    </select1>
    <select1 appearance="button" ref="/chapter2_2_exam_en/c2_2_q13">
      <label>13. What is the management of convulsion?</label>
      <item>
        <label>Hospitalization, check breathing, give bag mask ventilation or oxygen</label>
        <value>1</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>Check blood glucose, open IV channel</label>
        <value>2</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>Treat convulsion with phenobarbital</label>
        <value>3</value>
      </item>
    </select1>
    <select1 appearance="button" ref="/chapter2_2_exam_en/c2_2_q14">
      <label>14. What is the dose of phenobarbital for management of convulsion?</label>
      <item>
        <label>Loading dose 40mg/kg – IV</label>
        <value>1</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>Loading dose 20mg/kg. If convulsion persists give phenobarbital 10mg/kg up to 40mg/kg</label>
        <value>2</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>Loading dose 25mg/kg if convulsion persists give phenobarbital 10mg/kg up to 40mg/kg</label>
        <value>3</value>
      </item>
    </select1>
    <select1 appearance="button" ref="/chapter2_2_exam_en/c2_2_q15">
      <label>15. What are the signs of Meningitis?</label>
      <item>
        <label>Drowsy, lethargic or unconscious</label>
        <value>1</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>Convulsing, irritable</label>
        <value>2</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>Has a bulging fontanelle</label>
        <value>3</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>Has a high pitched cry</label>
        <value>4</value>
      </item>
    </select1>
    <select1 appearance="button" ref="/chapter2_2_exam_en/c2_2_q16">
      <label>16. What are the suitable antibiotics for management of Meningitis?</label>
      <item>
        <label>Injection Ampicillin – 50mg/kg dose - 12 hourly and Injection Gentamycin 5mg/kg dose – once</label>
        <value>1</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>Injection Ampicillin 50mg/kg dose - 12 hourly</label>
        <value>2</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>Injection Gentamycin 5mg/kg dose - once</label>
        <value>3</value>
      </item>
    </select1>
    <select1 appearance="button" ref="/chapter2_2_exam_en/c2_2_q17">
      <label>17. What are the indications of oxygen therapy?</label>
      <item>
        <label>Central Cyanosis, gasping, grunting, severe chest in-drawing</label>
        <value>1</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>Central Cyanosis</label>
        <value>2</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>Severe chest in-drawing</label>
        <value>3</value>
      </item>
    </select1>
    <select1 appearance="button" ref="/chapter2_2_exam_en/c2_2_q18">
      <label>18. What are the steps of thermal care during Hypothermia?</label>
      <item>
        <label>Well wrapped</label>
        <value>1</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>Keep in skin to skin position</label>
        <value>2</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>Check room temperature</label>
        <value>3</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>Monitor baby’s temperature</label>
        <value>4</value>
      </item>
    </select1>
    <select appearance="button" ref="/chapter2_2_exam_en/c2_2_q19">
      <label>19. What should you monitor for IV infusion?</label>
      <item>
        <label>Use monitoring sheet</label>
        <value>1</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>Calculate drip rate</label>
        <value>2</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>Check drip rate</label>
        <value>3</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>Weigh the baby daily</label>
        <value>4</value>
      </item>
      <item>
        <label>Watch for facial swelling</label>
        <value>5</value>
